[[File:Soil fertility analysis 6 Samples for Zn Mn & Cu by AAS.jpg|thumb|Testing soil fertility]] '''Soil quality''' is a measure of the condition of [[soil]] relative to the requirements of one or more biotic species and or to any [[human]] need or purpose.<ref>Johnson, D.L., S.H. Ambrose, T.J. Bassett, M.L. Bowen, D.E. Crummey, J.S. Isaacson, D.N. Johnson, P. Lamb, M. Saul, and A.E. Winter-Nelson. 1997. "Meanings of environmental terms". ''Journal of Environmental Quality'' 26: 581-589.</ref> According to the [[United States Department of Agriculture]] [[Natural Resources Conservation Service]], "Soil quality is the capacity of a specific kind of soil to function, within natural or managed ecosystem boundaries, to sustain plant and animal productivity, maintain or enhance water and [[air pollution|air quality]], and support human health and habitation.<ref name="NRCS2017">{{cite web|last1=USDA NRCS|title=Soil Quality: Basics: Definitions|url=http://soilquality.org/basics/definitions.html|website=soilquality.org|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref><ref name="Karlen1997">{{cite journal|last1=Karlen|first1=D. L.|last2=Mausbach|first2=M. J.|last3=Doran|first3=J. W.|last4=Cline|first4=R. G.|last5=Harris|first5=R. F.|last6=Schuman|first6=G. E.|title=Soil Quality: A Concept, Definition, and Framework for Evaluation (A Guest Editorial)|journal=Soil Science Society of America Journal|date=1997|volume=61|issue=1|pages=4-10|doi=10.2136/sssaj1997.03615995006100010001x|url=https://naldc.nal.usda.gov/download/16713/PDF|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref> The [[European Commission]]'s [[Joint Research Centre]] proposed a definition, stating that "Soil quality is an account of the soil's ability to provide ecosystem and social services through its capacities to perform its functions under changing conditions."<ref name=test>Tóth, G., Stolbovoy, V. and Montanarella, 2007. "[http://eusoils.jrc.ec.europa.eu/esdb_archive/eusoils_docs/other/EUR22721.pdf Soil Quality and Sustainability Evaluation - An integrated approach to support soil-related policies of the European Union] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029202634/http://eusoils.jrc.ec.europa.eu/esdb_archive/eusoils_docs/other/EUR22721.pdf |date=2013-10-29 }}", EUR 22721 EN. 40 pp. Office for Official Publications of the European Communities, [[Luxembourg]]. {{ISBN|978-92-79-05250-7}}.</ref>
Soil quality reflects how well a soil performs the functions of maintaining [[biodiversity]] and productivity, partitioning water and solute flow, filtering and buffering, [[nutrient cycle|nutrient cycling]], and providing support for plants and other structures. [[Soil management]] has a major impact on soil quality.
Soil quality in agricultural terms is measured on a scale of [[soil value]] (''Bodenwertzahl'') in [[Germany]].
Soil quality is related to soil function. Unlike water or air, for which established standards have been set, soil quality is difficult to define or quantify. Soil quality can be evaluated using the Soil Management Assessment Framework.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cherubin|first=Maurício Roberto|last2=Tormena|first2=Cássio Antônio|last3=Karlen|first3=Douglas L.|last4=Cherubin|first4=Maurício Roberto|last5=Tormena|first5=Cássio Antônio|last6=Karlen|first6=Douglas L.|date=00/2017|title=Soil Quality Evaluation Using the Soil Management Assessment Framework (SMAF) in Brazilian Oxisols with Contrasting Texture|url=http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?script=sci_abstract&pid=S0100-06832017000100503&lng=en&nrm=iso&tlng=en|journal=Revista Brasileira de Ciência do Solo|volume=41|doi=10.1590/18069657rbcs20160148|issn=0100-0683}}</ref>
